    "ocr_text": "X.
Apr. 29,1910.
Hon. George K. Turner,
Spokane,
Washington.
Dear Sir:
I am glad to have the opportunity to lay the matter before
you referred to in my telegram to you of the 27th instant, and your
wire that you will be in Spokane until May tenth; that you will
sail for the Hague and return to the United States by October first,
seems to give the opportunity which I am seeking, that is, your
assistance in the appeal of the Hatters' case from the Federal Cir-
cuit Court of Connecticut to the Court of Appeals and perhaps if
necessary to the Supreme Court of the United States.
First and foremost, I should say that I have been entirely
dissatisfied in the way the case has been handled all the way through
and when the question was certified to by the Federal Court of
Appeals to the Supreme Court for decision, and later the argument
made thereon, after listening to the argument I expressed to our
friends and to their counsel my dissatisfaction in the most emphatic
terms as to the manner in which the case was presented and argued
by the Hatters' attorneys. Of course you know that inst the United
States Supreme Court decided that under the certified question D. E.
Loew and Company could maintain a course of action under the Sherman",

The writer expresses the desire to discuss a matter previously mentioned in a telegram. The writer is dissatisfied with how the case has been handled and presented, particularly criticizing the Hatters' attorneys.",
